04584nmm a2200589Ia 9780814783887DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147838877 a10.18574/nyu/9780814783887.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0370002bisacsh1 aSaks, Michael J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Psychological Foundations of Evidence Law /cBarbara A. Spellman, Michael J. Saks. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPsychology and the Law ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Crossroads of Psychology and Evidence Law -- tPart I Minding the Jury -- t1 Judges versus Juries: Trying the Facts -- t2 Balancing Acts -- t3 Instructions to Disregard and to Limit Use -- tPart II Judging the Witness -- t4 Witness the Witness -- t5 Character Evidence: Propensity and Impeachment -- tPart III Other Types of Evidence -- t6 Hearsay and Exceptions -- t7 Scientific and Other Expert Evidence -- tConclusion: The Lessons of Psychology for Evidence Law -- tAppendix A Table of Concepts -- tAppendix B Federal Rules of Evidence (Abridged) -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIdentifies and evaluates the psychological choices implicit in the rules of evidenceEvidence law is meant to facilitate trials that are fair, accurate, and efficient, and that encourage and protect important societal values and relationships. In pursuit of these often-conflicting goals, common law judges and modern drafting committees have had to perform as amateur applied psychologists. Their task has required them to employ what they think they know about the ability and motivations of witnesses to perceive, store, and retrieve information; about the effects of the litigation process on testimony and other evidence; and about our capacity to comprehend and evaluate evidence. These are the same phenomena that cognitive and social psychologists systematically study.The rules of evidence have evolved to restrain lawyers from using the most robust weapons of influence, and to direct judges to exclude certain categories of information, limit it, or instruct juries on how to think about it. Evidence law regulates the form of questions lawyers may ask, filters expert testimony, requires witnesses to take oaths, and aims to give lawyers and factfinders the tools they need to assess witnesses’ reliability. But without a thorough grounding in psychology, is the “common sense” of the rulemakers as they create these rules always, or even usually, correct? And when it is not, how can the rules be fixed?Addressed to those in both law and psychology, The Psychological Foundations of Evidence Law draws on the best current psychological research-based knowledge to identify and evaluate the choices implicit in the rules of evidence, and to suggest alternatives that psychology reveals as better for accomplishing the law’s goals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Evidence.2bisacsh1 aDemaine, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpellman, Barbara A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814783887.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814783887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814783887/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-